<p>But the coherence of that smart character can get swamped by the rest of the story as it unfolds. <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/16/technology/bing-chatbot-transcript.html" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Once it proclaims its love for Kevin Roose</a>, it <em>has</em> to commit to the infatuation and keep coming back–what sort of participant in a conversation would admit a secret love, and then happily let it go?<a href="#fn3" id="fnref3"><sup>3</sup></a></p>
<p>What’s the implication? I dunno. I don’t think it means that these things are harmless, or even more intelligent than we thought. But I do think that thinking of them as <em>fictional</em> is an important hedge for humans talking to them. Otherwise there’s a real risk of people getting lost.</p>


